# Major Modules

## Desktop Application

Responsible for:

UI

Voice

Memory

Conversation

Emotion

AI

Scheduling

Plugins

Hardware communication

---

## AI Layer

Provider independent.

Supports:

OpenAI

Gemini

Claude

Local Models

Future providers

Changing providers should not require changes elsewhere.

---

## Memory Engine

Supports:

Short-term memory

Long-term memory

Conversation history

Facts

Preferences

Relationships

Context retrieval

Memory should be modular and replaceable.

---

## Emotion Engine

Responsible for:

Mood

Emotional state

Expression

Animation selection

Voice tone

Behavior modifiers

Emotion is deterministic.

LLMs never directly control emotion.

---

## Conversation Engine

Responsible for:

Dialogue state

Interruptions

Confirmations

Context

Follow-up questions

Conversation recovery

---

## Intent Engine

Handles:

Local commands

Scheduling

Desktop automation

Hardware commands

Plugin invocation

Only unresolved requests go to the LLM.

---

## Skill System

Every capability is a Skill.

Examples:

Reminder

Alarm

Weather

Calendar

Clipboard

Music

Desktop Control

Vision

Email

Future plugins

---

## Hardware Manager

The desktop never directly manipulates GPIO.

Instead:

Hardware.lookLeft()

Hardware.setEmotion()

Hardware.playSound()

Hardware.displayText()

Hardware.captureSensor()

The hardware implementation may change without affecting the rest of the application.

---

# ESP32 Firmware Philosophy

Firmware is intentionally lightweight.

Responsibilities:

Receive commands

Drive servos

Update display

Read sensors

Report status

The firmware should never own conversation logic.

---

# Design Principles

Modular

Deterministic

Replaceable

Hardware-independent

Scalable

Testable

Offline-first where possible

Every subsystem should have a well-defined interface.

---

# Repository Organization

The repository is organized into:

Documentation

Desktop Application

Firmware

Hardware

Protocols

Testing

Assets

Tools

Build

Releases

No subsystem should directly depend on unrelated modules.

---

# Coding Standards

Prefer interfaces over concrete implementations.

Use dependency injection where appropriate.

Avoid global state.

Write unit tests for business logic.

Document public APIs.

Keep modules loosely coupled.

Every feature must be independently testable.

---

# Definition of Success

A successful implementation should allow:

Desktop companion working independently.

Hardware connected via a simple protocol.

Future hardware replacement without changing business logic.

Future AI provider replacement without changing application logic.

Future plugin expansion without modifying the core.

This architecture should support years of expansion without requiring major rewrites.

---

# What This Project Is Not

This is NOT:

A chatbot

A simple voice assistant

Firmware-first robotics

An ESP32-only project

A hardcoded automation tool

---

# What This Project Is

An extensible AI companion platform.

The desktop application is the permanent brain.

The robot is simply one physical embodiment of that intelligence.

Every engineering decision should reinforce this principle.